Spatial lag of explanatory variables¶

Spatial lag assumes that conditions of your neighborhood has an affect on you. For example, if you are studying the correlation between, let's say, obesity rates and the amount of fast food chains, you would intuitively understand that someone's obesity rate is not only affected by the number of fast food chains on their block, but also the number of fast food chains in their neighborhood, city, region, or even country. So knowing this, the explanatory variables to test when finding out what affects obesity rates wouldn't just be number of fast food chains in that postcode - it would be number of fast food chains with 3, 10, 30km of that post code as well.

The same logic can be applied to our analysis - kg as secondary resource received in one postcode isn't only affected by kg of waste produced in that particular postcode, it's more likely affected by waste produced in postcodes within a 3, 10, 30km radius. In this notebook, we will try out calculating spatial lag by using the LMA dataset as an example. While our dependent variable is log(kg received) for each postcode, our (test) explanatory variable is log(kg processed) within 3, 10, 30km of that postcode. The outcome of this notebook is therefore a dataframe that contains the columns:

  • postcode
  • log(kg received)
  • log(kg processed) within 3km radius
  • log(kg processed) within 10km radius
  • log(kg processed) within 30km radius

# read dataframe 
df = feather.read_dataframe('../data/lma/af_2019-2020_matched-codes.feather')
df = df[~df.gnc.isna()] # extract rows with gnc
df = df[df.year == 2019] # only looking at numbers in 2019
df.eaPostcode = df.eaPostcode.str[:4].astype('int64') # convert to pc4 
df.herPostcode = df.herPostcode.str[:4].astype('int64')
df = df[['eaPostcode','herPostcode', 'kg']]

# make df for received per pc
dfEa = df.groupby(['eaPostcode']).sum().kg.reset_index()
dfEa.rename(columns={'eaPostcode': 'postcode', 'kg': 'kg_received'}, inplace=True)

# make df for processed per pc
dfHer = df.groupby(['herPostcode']).sum().kg.reset_index()
dfHer.rename(columns={'herPostcode': 'postcode', 'kg': 'kg_processed'}, inplace=True)

# merge with nlpc4 
nl_pc4 = gpd.read_file('../data/spatial-data/nl_pc4.shp')
nl_pc4 = nl_pc4[['PC4', 'geometry']]
nl_pc4.PC4 = nl_pc4.PC4.astype('int64')
nl_pc4 = nl_pc4.to_crs('EPSG:28992') # reprojecting to amersfoort CRS (where units is not degrees but meters, see https://epsg.io/28992)
df = pd.merge(nl_pc4, dfEa, how='left', left_on='PC4', right_on='postcode')
df = pd.merge(df, dfHer, how='left', left_on='PC4', right_on='postcode')
df = df.drop(labels=['postcode_x', 'postcode_y'], axis=1)
df = df.rename(columns={'PC4': 'pc'})

# column with log_kg
def log(x): 
    if x > 0: 
        return np.log(x)
    else: 
        return 0
df['log_kg_received'] = df.kg_received.map(lambda x: log(x))
df['log_kg_processed'] = df.kg_processed.map(lambda x: log(x))

# add centroids
df = gpd.GeoDataFrame(df)
df['centroid'] = df.geometry.centroid
df = df.fillna(0)

# display
print('rows, columns: {}'.format(df.shape))
df = df[['pc', 'geometry', 'centroid', 'kg_received', 'kg_processed', 'log_kg_received', 'log_kg_processed']]

Spatial weights¶

Using the pySAL spatial weights module, we create the (kernel) spatial weight matrices for 3, 10, 30km radiuses. In other words, for each postcode, we are defining which other postcodes are within a 3, 10, and 30km radius. Handy links below:

  • https://pysal.org/notebooks/lib/libpysal/weights.html
  • https://splot.readthedocs.io/en/stable/users/tutorials/weights.html#pysal-spatial-weight-types
  • https://pysal.org/libpysal/generated/libpysal.weights.DistanceBand.html
  • http://darribas.org/gds_scipy16/ipynb_md/03_spatial_weights.html

wd30.transform = 'r'
wd50 = lp.weights.DistanceBand.from_dataframe(df, threshold=50000, silence_warnings=True)
wd50.transform = 'r'

Spatial lag¶

Using the spatial weights we just created, we calculate the following for each postcode:

  • average log(kg) received within 4, 10, 30km radius (spatial lag)
  • total log(kg) received within 4, 10, 30km radius
  • average log(kg) processed within 4, 10, 30km radius (spatial lag)
  • total log(kg) processed within 4, 10, 30km radius
  • average log(kg) created within 4, 10, 30km radius (spatial lag)
  • total log(kg) created within 4, 10, 30km radius

Average secondary resources received within 4, 10, 30km radius¶

In [111]:
# spatial lag for log values
tName = ['av_received_4km', 'av_received_10km', 'av_received_30km', 'av_received_50km']
wds = [wd4, wd10, wd30, wd50] # spatial weights of 3, 10, 30km radius 

# calculate spatial lag 
for i in range(4): 
    y = df['log_kg_received']
    ylag = lp.weights.lag_spatial(wds[i], y) 
    df[tName[i]] = ylag

# plot log(kg)
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,5,figsize=(5*5,5))
df.plot(ax=ax[0], column='log_kg_received', cmap='OrRd', legend=True)
ax[0].set_title('log_kg_received')
ax[0].axis('off')

# plot spatial lag for log(kg)
for i in range(4): 
    df.plot(ax=ax[i+1], column=tName[i], cmap='OrRd', legend=True)
    ax[i+1].set_title(tName[i])
    ax[i+1].axis('off')

# display 
plt.show()

# total kg received at 4, 10, 30km 
tName = ['tot_received_4km', 'tot_received_10km', 'tot_received_30km', 'tot_received_50km']
wds = [wd4, wd10, wd30, wd50] # spatial weights of 3, 10, 30km radius 

# calculate total kg received using the 4 spatial weights (wds)
for i in range(4): 
    t = tName[i] # not sure why this needs to be done, but without it, returns error 'index out of range'. 
    wd = wds[i]
    totalReceived = []
    for i in range(len(df)): 
        total = df.iloc[list(wd[i].keys())].log_kg_received.sum()
        totalReceived.append(total)
    df[t] = pd.Series(totalReceived)

# read df 
wp = feather.read_dataframe('../data/lma/ontv_2019.feather')
wp = wp[['Ontdoener Postcode', 'Locatie van Herkomst Postcode', 'Locatie van Herkomst Land', 'Verwerker Postcode', 'Totaal Gewicht (KG) Totaal']]
wp.rename(columns={'Ontdoener Postcode': 'ontPc', 'Locatie van Herkomst Postcode': 'herPc', 'Locatie van Herkomst Land': 'land', 
                   'Verwerker Postcode': 'verPc', 'Totaal Gewicht (KG) Totaal': 'kg_produced'}, inplace=True)
wp.land = wp.land.str.lower()

# pick postcode (prefer herkomst)
def pcPicker(row): 
    if row.herPc == None: 
        return row.ontPc
    else: 
        return row.herPc
wp['pc'] = wp.apply(lambda row: pcPicker(row), axis=1)

# drop empty postcodes, irrelevant rows, rows from other countries
wp = wp[~wp.pc.isna()]
wp = wp[['pc', 'land', 'kg_produced']]
wp.land = wp.land.fillna('') # dropped some NL flows here, will need to use regex to find postcodes of NL 
wp = wp[wp.land == 'nederland'] # only pick nl flows 
wp['lenPc'] = wp.pc.map(lambda x: len(x)) # drop wrongly inputted pcs 
wp = wp[wp.lenPc <= 6]
wp.pc = wp.pc.str[:4]
wp = wp[wp.pc != 'M278']
wp.pc = wp.pc.astype('int64')

# group by pc
wp = wp[['pc', 'kg_produced']]
wp = wp.groupby('pc').sum().reset_index()

# add pc geometry
wp = pd.merge(nl_pc4, wp, how='left', left_on='PC4', right_on='pc')
wp = wp[['PC4', 'geometry', 'kg_produced']]

# display
print(wp.shape)
